2) Functional Interface (Very Important)

⭐5. What is a Functional Interface?
Answer:
A functional interface is an interface with exactly one abstract method.
It can have multiple default/static methods, but only one abstract.

Example:
@FunctionalInterface
interface Demo {
    void show(); // only 1 abstract method
}

Examples from Java:
Runnable
Callable
Comparator

⭐6. Why @FunctionalInterface annotation is used?
Answer:
It ensures the interface remains functional. If someone adds another abstract method, it gives compile-time error.

⭐7. Can a functional interface have default methods?
Answer:
Yes. It can have any number of default and static methods.

⭐8. Examples of built-in functional interfaces?
Answer:
Predicate<T> → returns Boolean   (test)                    # Predicate<Integer> p = x -> x > 10;
Function<T,R> → takes input, returns output  (apply)       # Function<Integer, Integer> f = x -> x * 2;
Consumer<T> → takes input, returns nothing  (accept)       # Consumer<String> c = s -> System.out.println(s);
Supplier<T> → returns output, takes nothing (get)          # Supplier<Integer> s = () -> 100;

⭐9. Difference between Predicate and Function?
Answer:
Predicate → used for conditions / filtering, returns boolean
Function → used for transformation, returns value

⭐10. Why we need Functional Interface
Answer : We need functional interfaces because they provide a single abstract method, which allows Java to use lambda expressions 
and pass behavior as an argument without ambiguity.

